      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "Refactor HTTP egress around external proxy enforcement",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nThis PR replaces OpenClaw's old scattered in-process SSRF fetch guard with a smaller HTTP egress architecture:\n\n- `proxy.enabled=true` plus an operator-managed external proxy is the high-assurance SSRF and egress-control boundary.\n- OpenClaw no longer maintains the broad `fetchWithSsrFGuard` / DNS pinning / per-call SSRF policy framework as a public plugin SDK or app-wide fetch API.\n- Stock direct mode still keeps a narrow guard for OpenClaw-owned fetches of arbitrary untrusted URLs.\n- App-owned outbound HTTP mechanics are centralized through the egress helper instead of repeated local fetch loops.\n\n## What Changed\n\n- Added the canonical HTTP egress helper in `src/infra/net/egress-fetch.ts`.\n- Migrated OpenClaw-owned runtime fetch paths, including web fetch, media/input URL fetches, link understanding, citation redirects, marketplace archive downloads, skill install downloads, MCP HTTP, provider transport fetches, and related provider/plugin runtime fetches.\n- Removed the old `fetchWithSsrFGuard` API and retired old per-call SSRF policy/config knobs.\n- Removed public SSRF SDK surfaces as a breaking SDK cleanup:\n  - `openclaw/plugin-sdk/ssrf-runtime`\n  - `openclaw/plugin-sdk/ssrf-policy`\n  - `openclaw/plugin-sdk/ssrf-dispatcher`\n  - SSRF helper re-exports from `openclaw/plugin-sdk/security-runtime`\n- Kept retained internal/private network-policy primitives only where OpenClaw-owned bundled/runtime code still needs them.\n- Replaced the old raw-fetch guard script with `scripts/check-runtime-http-egress-boundary.mjs`, which blocks raw app-owned runtime fetches and retired SSRF guard vocabulary.\n- Updated docs, doctor migrations, package/export checks, and Plugin SDK contract tests for the new boundary.\n\n## Behavior\n\nWhen `proxy.enabled=false`, OpenClaw's untrusted URL helper rejects local/private/internal targets for OpenClaw-owned arbitrary URL fetches by default, including localhost, loopback, link-local, RFC1918 private networks, known metadata hosts, DNS results resolving to blocked ranges, and redirect targets resolving to blocked ranges.\n\nThis direct-mode check is a narrow stock safety guard. It is not a complete SSRF defense and is not a substitute for an external egress proxy in high-assurance deployments.\n\nWhen `proxy.enabled=true`, OpenClaw routes app-owned HTTP egress through the configured proxy and does not try to duplicate the proxy's comprehensive destination policy in application code.\n\nOperator-configured endpoints, fixed product/vendor endpoints, and transport-owned fetch behavior are treated separately from arbitrary untrusted web URLs.\n\n## Breaking Changes\n\n- Plugins can no longer import the removed SSRF SDK subpaths or `fetchWithSsrFGuard` / `GUARDED_FETCH_MODE` style APIs.\n- Plugins should use ordinary `fetch` or supported generic fetch runtime mechanics where appropriate.\n- High-assurance destination policy belongs at `proxy.enabled=true` plus the operator-managed external proxy.\n- Plugin-specific allowlist validation should stay local to the plugin when the plugin owns a special protocol or redirect flow.\n\n## Out Of Scope\n\nThis PR does not claim full SSRF coverage for Browser/CDP, subprocesses, sandbox executors, Docker/SSH boundaries, MCP stdio children, native addons, or non-Node transport libraries. Those remain separate defense-in-depth follow-ups.\n\n## Verification\n\n### Focused local checks\n\n- Focused unit and boundary tests for the egress helper, migrated fetch paths, plugin SDK contracts, doctor migrations, package/release checks, and raw-fetch boundary checks.\n- `node scripts/check-runtime-http-egress-boundary.mjs`\n- `node scripts/check-plugin-sdk-subpath-exports.mjs`\n- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs test/release-check.test.ts src/plugins/contracts/plugin-sdk-package-contract-guardrails.test.ts src/plugins/sdk-alias.test.ts src/plugins/plugin-sdk-native-resolver.test.ts`\n- `pnpm docs:check-mdx`\n- `pnpm build`\n- `git diff --check`\n- `.agents/skills/autoreview/scripts/autoreview --mode local`: clean, no accepted/actionable findings.\n\n### Package smoke\n\n- Provider/id: `blacksmith-testbox`, `tbx_01ktnh39xjqvzaqyvnk4tek7bf`\n- Actions run: `27188175859`\n- Verified the packaged SDK/public export surface after the removal.\n- Confirmed retired SSRF SDK/runtime exports are absent from the public package surface.\n\n### External proxy E2E\n\n- Provider/id: `blacksmith-testbox`, `tbx_01ktnh8w3mgdvg1rgvd8z4tmr8`\n- Actions run: `27188302520`\n- Verified `proxy.enabled=true` routes covered runtime fetches through the configured external proxy.\n- Verified proxy-mode fetch and redirect behavior remains intact for the covered helper scenarios.\n\n### AWS product-path proof\n\n- Provider/id: `aws`, `cbx_5b6e8d6f5c94`\n- Exercised OpenClaw product call paths against an AWS-hosted target, honeypot, and proof proxy fixture:\n  - `web_fetch`\n  - link understanding\n  - citation redirect resolution\n  - remote media fetch\n  - input-file URL fetch\n  - marketplace archive download\n  - skill install download\n  - MCP HTTP same-origin fetch\n  - operator-configured endpoint fetch\n- Verified direct-mode untrusted URL paths block private/local/metadata-style targets before honeypot access.\n- Verified proxy-mode paths route through the proof proxy and apply proxy allow/block decisions.\n- Verified operator-configured endpoint behavior remains distinct from arbitrary untrusted URL behavior.\n\n### Marketplace private-redirect proof\n\n- Provider/id: `aws`, `cbx_9bd99a3d87b9`\n- AWS runs: `run_b117a76160d3`, `run_714cc4109634`, `run_b47458f97c57`, `run_62972875e8be`, `run_636a90f349b7`, `run_0058dee2fdac`\n- Verified archive-looking marketplace source URLs enter the archive download path, then block private redirect targets in direct mode before honeypot access.\n- Verified proxy mode routes the same redirect flow through the proof proxy, where the public archive fixture is allowed and the private redirect target is blocked.\n- Honeypot hits remained `0` for the private redirect target in both modes.\n\n## Real Behavior Proof\n\nBehavior addressed: OpenClaw-owned arbitrary URL fetch paths no longer depend on the old scattered `fetchWithSsrFGuard` architecture, while stock direct mode still blocks local/private/metadata-style targets for untrusted URL fetches.\n\nReal environment tested: Local focused tests, Blacksmith Testbox, and AWS Crabbox live network topology proof.\n\nExact steps or command run after this patch: Focused test lanes, runtime egress boundary check, package smoke, external proxy E2E, AWS product-path proof, targeted marketplace archive redirect proof, docs check, build, and autoreview.\n\nEvidence after fix: Direct-mode untrusted URL fetches block private redirect targets before honeypot access; proxy-mode fetches route through the external proof proxy and are blocked by proxy policy before honeypot access.\n\nObserved result after fix: All planned proof rows passed for this refactor's stated scope.\n\nWhat was not tested: Browser/CDP, subprocess, sandbox executor, Docker, SSH, MCP stdio, native addon, and non-Node transport boundaries.\n",
